text: • Another middle school conducted the same type of fundraiser as the middle school in the problems. The banner shows the goals for each grade.
a. Write three statements that the principal could make when comparing the goals each grade has set.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • The sixth graders plan to raise $60 more than the fifth graders.
  • The fifth graders plan to raise half the amount that the seventh graders want to raise.
  • The eighth graders plan to raise the most money.
  • For every 1 dollar the fifth graders raise, the seventh graders plan to raise 2 dollars.
b. The teachers set a goal of $225. Write two statements that the principal could use to compare this goal to the eighth graders' goal.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • The teachers want to raise $75 less than the eighth graders.
  • The teachers' goal is 3/4 of the eighth graders' goal.
  • For every $45 the teachers raise, the eighth graders will riase $60.
There are 12 pens and 24 pencils in the classroom container.

a. Consider this statement:

For every 2 pens, there are 4 pencils.

Do you agree with this statement? Explain.

Yes, I agree with this statement. Students may multiply the 2 by 6 and the 4 by 6 to get 12 pens and 24 pencils. Others mat start with "For every 2 pens, there are 4 pencils." We can show this is equivalent to "12 pens and 24 pencils" by finding the multiples of 2 pens and 4 pencils. This can be observed in the following table:
b. Write two or more statements comparing the number of pens in the class to the number of pencils.

Answers may vary. Possible statements:

  • There are twice the number of pencils as the number of pens in the classroom container.
  • There are 12 less pens than pencils in the classroom container.
  • There are half as many pens as pencils in the classroom container.
  • For every 1 pen, there are 2 pencils.
The members of the Central Middle School French Club make 30 fruit skewers. They use green grapes, blueberries, and purple grapes. They make the following claims.

Claim 1

For every 90 green grapes on the skewers, they need 60 purple grapes.

Claim 2

The club likes green grapes better than blueberries.

Claim 3

For every 1 blueberry, there is 1 purple grape.

Claim 4

The ratio of purple to green grapes is 3 to 2.

Claim 5

There are more green grapes than purple grapes.
a. Which of the claims are true?
b. Which of the claims are ratios?

Claims 1, 3, and 6. Claim 4 is an incorrect ratio.

Discussion points:

Claim 1 True Ratio

Claim 2 Can't determine—not ratio

Claim 3 True Ratio

Claim 4 False—Incorrect Ratio

Claim 5 True—not ratio

Claim 6 True Ratio

Eduardo, Karim, and Shawn are training for the school cross- country team. One day, they report the distances they ran as a comparison statements.
a. Eduardo says he ran twice as far as Karim. Give three possibilities for the distances each could have run.

Answers may vary. Possible distances:

  • Eduardo: 3 km, Karim: 1.5 km
  • Eduardo: 10 km, Karim: 5 km
  • Eduardo: 4 km, Karim: 2 km
b. Karim says that the ratio of the distance he ran to the distance Shawn ran is 4:3. Give three possibilities for the distances each could have run.

Answers may vary, Possible distances.

  • Karim: 4 km, Shawn: 3 km
  • Karim: 6 km, Shawn: 4.5 km
  • Karim: 12 km, Shawn: 9 km
Eduardo ran the furthest. If he ran twice as far as Karim and Karim ran further than Shawn (that is what is implied by the ratio 4:3), then Eduardo ran farther than both Karim and Shawn.
Fahari saw a fish tank that had 9 blue fish and 15 orange fish. Find the ratio that incorrectly describes the fish tank, and explain why it is incorrect.

a. For every 24 fish, 9 were blue.

b. The ratio of orange to blue fish is 9 to 15.

c. For every 3 blue fish, there were 5 orange fish.

d. The ratio of blue fish to the total is 9 to 24.
b is false; the ratio of orange to blue fish is 15 to 9

Desmond put candles on his brother's birthday cake. He used 5 blue candles, 5 green candles, and 4 red candles. Mark each ratio as true (accurate) or false (not accurate). If not accurate, try to revise to make it true. Which ratios are part to part and which are part to whole?
a. The ratio of blue to green is 1 to 1.
b. For every 14 candles, there are 4 red.
c. For every 3 candles, there is one of each color.
F, incorrect part-to-whole. A correct part-to-whole might be: for every 14 candles there are 5 blue.
d. The ratio of red to blue is 5:4.
F, incorrect part-to-part. A correct part to part might be: the ratio of red to blue is 4:5

The sixth graders make a new box that holds 15 cupcakes. They want 10 green cupcakes for every 5 white cupcakes in the box. Write at least two ratios that are part to part and two ratios that are part to whole to describe this new box of cupcakes.

Possible answers include:

Part-to-Part:

For every 10 green cupcakes, there are 5 white cupcakes.

The ratio of white to green cupcakes is 5 to 10.

For every 2 green cupcakes, there is 1 white cupcake.

Part-to-Whole:

For every 15 cupcakes, there are 5 white cupcakes.

The ratio of green cupcakes to total cupcakes is 10 to 15.

For every 3 cupcakes, there is 1 white cupcake

The ratio of green cupcakes to total cupcakes is 2 to 3.

A fruit bar is 5 inches long. The bar will be split into two pieces. For each situation, find the lengths of the two pieces.
a. One piece is 3/10 of the whole bar.
3/10 of the whole bar equals 1.5 inches. Thus, the other piece is 3.5 inches.
b. One piece is 1 inch longer than the other.
If one piece is 1 inch longer than the other, this would mean one piece is 3 inches and one piece is 2 inches.
Use the bar graph, which shows the number of cans of juice three sixth grade classes drank, to answer ACE 11a-e
a. In each class, estimate the ratio of cans of orange juice to total cans.

Mr. Chan: 1 can of orange juice for every 3 total cans

Mr. Will: 1 can of orange juice for every 4 total cans

Ms. Luke: 1 can of orange juice for every 4 total cans
b. In each class, estimate what fraction of the cans were orange juice.

Mr. Chan's Class: About 1/3 is orange juice.

Mr. Will's Class: About 1/4 is orange juice

Mr. Luke's Class: About 1/4 is orange juice.
c. In which class, would you say orange juice was most popular?
Mr. Chan's classroom, because 1/3 is greater than 1/4.
d. Students in Mr. Chan's class drank a total of 10 cans of orange juice. About how many cans of orange juice did the students in each of the other two classes drink?
Mr. Will: about 7 cans of orange juice; Ms. Luke: about 8 cans of orange juice.
e. About how many total cans of juice did each of the three classes drink?
Mr. Chang: 30 cans of juice; Mr. Will: about 28 cans of juice; Ms. Luke: about 32 cans of juice.

a. Miguel says that you can easily separate numbers that are not divisible by 2 into two equal parts. Do you agree? Why or why not?
Miguel is correct. If a number is divisible by 2, you can separate it into 2 equal halves.
b. Manny says that is Miguel is correct, then you can easily separate numbers that are divisible by 3 into three equal parts. Do you agree? Why or why not?
Manny is also correct. If a number is divisible by 3, you can separate it into 3 groups of equal size, or into thirds.
c. Lupe says that if any number is divisible by n, you can easily separate it into n equal parts. Do you agree with her? Explain.
Lupe is correct. If a number is divisible by n, you can separate it into n groups of equal size, or into nths

a. It is possible that there was only one other person to share with? Explain.
b. Is it possible that Dario was sharing the pizzas with 5 other people? Explain.
c. Is it possible that Dario was sharing the pizzas with 11 other people? Explain.

a. Can you think of a medium box that keeps the same ratio between green and white cupcakes as the small box? Explain.
